Assignment No. 3
Overview
Installed cert-manager and configured a private self-signed Certificate Authority to issue TLS certificates for the cluster. Enabled HTTPS on the Envoy Gateway using a cert-manager-issued wildcard certificate covering all three application hostnames.
Components Created
•	Bootstrap self-signed Issuer
•	Root CA Certificate (imesh-root-ca)
•	ClusterIssuer (imesh-ca-issuer)
•	Wildcard TLS Certificate (company-local-tls)
•	Kubernetes TLS Secret (company-local-tls)
•	HTTPS listener on company-gateway (port 443)
Implementation Details
•	Installed cert-manager via Helm into the cert-manager namespace, with clusterResourceNamespace=cert-manager so the CA secret and ClusterIssuer resolve correctly.
•	Created a bootstrap self-signed Issuer, used once to mint our own root CA certificate (isCA: true).
•	Created a ClusterIssuer backed by that root CA secret, so it can issue real certificates cluster-wide.
•	Requested a single wildcard Certificate (*.company.local, with explicit SANs for web/api/test.company.local) from the ClusterIssuer — one cert covers all three hosts instead of three separate ones.
•	Added a second listener (https, port 443, mode: Terminate) to the existing company-gateway, referencing the company-local-tls Secret, alongside the existing HTTP listener.
•	Existing HTTPRoutes automatically attached to the new HTTPS listener without modification, since Gateway API attaches routes by hostname/allowedRoutes match, not per-listener config.



